A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA) on several grounds, including: 

1. if the marriage was performed when one of the parties was already married and the previous spouse was still alive (Section 12(1)(a) HMA); 
2. if the marriage was performed when one of the parties was suffering from a mental disorder (Section 12(1)(b) HMA); 
3. if the marriage was performed when the bride was pregnant by another man at the time of marriage (Section 12(1)(c) HMA); 
4. if the marriage was performed when one of the parties was impotent or unable to consummate the marriage (Section 12(1)(a) and (d) HMA); 
5. if the marriage was performed when one of the parties had not attained the minimum age for marriage (Section 12(1)(e) HMA); 
6. if the marriage was performed when the parties were sapindas (related by blood or marriage) (Section 12(1)(f) HMA); 
7. if the marriage was performed when the parties were not of the same gotra (Section 12(1)(g) HMA) for certain communities.

